<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06131170 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06131170 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  It turned out to be one of the worst days in Moffett Field Naval Air Stationhistory. People at the Santa Clara County base were still jubilant over thevictory in the Persian Gulf war when they received the news that morning ofMarch 21: Two P-3C Orions had collided off San Diego during a routine switchand 27 men were killed.;    Poppa 3 Juliet was ending its eight-hour-plusmission, readying to turn its submarine patrol task to Yankee 9 Charlie.Something went wrong and the two planes collided, creating a terrifying&quot;shower of glowing embers.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MOFFETT SAYS 'THANK YOU'  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Today on the Peninsula  </MEMO><TEXT>     People at Moffett immediately went to work to raise money for thesurvivors. And the results have been quite good, said William H. Brandow,chaplain of Branch 101 of the Fleet Reserves Association. &quot;I'm very pleased.&quot;;   The $27,000 goal has been reached, Brandow said, and will be distributedevenly among the survivors, he said.;    People from all over the countryresponded. A $10 check here, a $15 one there. Brandow has received checks fromFlorida, from the Midwest, &quot;a couple from Kansas, one from Texas.&quot; Closer tohome, people at the base, as well as from nearby NASA/Ames, lent a helpinghand.;    Thank-you notes have been sent to those who can be traced, but someof the checks were from anonymous donors. &quot;I want to give a general thank youin the newspapers,&quot; Brandow said. &quot;There are quite a few who aren't going toget personal thank-yous.&quot;;    ROCK'N'TIME: Some aspiring rock 'n' rollers inPalo Alto are getting pretty amped. No doubt. It's almost time for another&quot;Battle of the Bands&quot; contest to see who rips the best. Five bands from PaloAlto, Gunn and Mid-Peninsula high schools will duke it out.;    &quot;Basically, weare trying to give the bands a chance to see what they can do,&quot; said DannGraham, the city's youth music coordinator.;    The &quot;battle&quot; is part of thecity's efforts to steer youths away from drugs and other unsavory things.;   It will be the third such battle this year. Organizers from the cityrecreation department hope to put on the show every month or so.;    Theconcerts start at 7:30 p.m. Saturday and last until midnight, at Mitchell ParkCommunity Center. Then there will be a final, best-of-the-best outdoor concerton June 22 at the El Camino Park. Should be a lot of acoustical fireworks.;   EARTH BAY: One of the coolest things about the Bay Area is its open space. The&quot;green belt,&quot; as it's called, is often threatened by development. ThePeninsula Conservation Center, as its name implies, would like to keep thegreen belt green. Marcia Ruf of the Green Belt Alliance will drop by thecenter on May 22 to talk about how important it is to preserve the green andpromote responsible development. Her talk is part of the center's brown-baglunch series, so bring something to munch. Bring a $2 donation, too, to helpkeep the series going.;    The talk will last from noon to 1 p.m. at thecenter, 2448 Watson Court, Palo Alto. For more information, call (415)494-9301.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  De Tran column  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910510  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  531  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday May 10, 199100131170,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>